messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full path:
  /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas

- All HTTP methods acceptable:
  false

- HEAD:
  false

- POST:
  true

- OPTIONS:
  false

- TRACE:
  false

- GET:
  true

- PUT:
  false

- DELETE:
  false

- PATCH:
  false

Explanation:
- The controller class has no class-level @RequestMapping, so each method-level @RequestMapping value is the full request path.
- In the source, there are two explicit mappings for the path "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas":
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas", method = RequestMethod.GET)
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas", method = RequestMethod.POST)
  These make GET and POST explicitly acceptable for that exact path.
- No mapping in the code declares RequestMethod.HEAD, RequestMethod.OPTIONS, RequestMethod.TRACE, RequestMethod.PUT, RequestMethod.DELETE, or RequestMethod.PATCH for this path, so those methods are not acceptable according to the code (per the instruction not to assume implicit behavior such as automatic HEAD support).
- Note: DELETE and PUT are present in the controller but they apply to the different path "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}", not to "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas".
